---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
  "itemListElement": [
    {"@type":"ListItem","position":1,"name":"Home","item":"https://privacycomply.io/"},
    {"@type":"ListItem","position":2,"name":"Reviews","item":"https://privacycomply.io/best-cookie-consent-tools-2026.html"},
    {"@type":"ListItem","position":3,"name":"CookieYes Review","item":"https://privacycomply.io/cookieyes-review.html"}
  ]
};

const reviewSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Review",
  "itemReviewed": {
    "@type": "SoftwareApplication",
    "name": "CookieYes",
    "applicationCategory": "BusinessApplication",
    "operatingSystem": "Web",
    "offers": {"@type":"Offer","price":"10","priceCurrency":"USD"}
  },
  "reviewRating": {"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"4.8","bestRating":"5"},
  "author": {"@type":"Organization","name":"PrivacyComply"},
  "datePublished": "2026-06-05",
  "publisher": {"@type":"Organization","name":"PrivacyComply","url":"https://privacycomply.io/"},
  "reviewBody": "After 30 days on a real WordPress site, CookieYes is the best cookie consent tool for most websites in 2026. Fast setup, real free tier, full GDPR/CCPA/PIPEDA/LGPD coverage, native Google Consent Mode v2."
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {"@type":"Question","name":"Is CookieYes really free?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes — the free tier covers up to 25,000 page views per month with full GDPR, CCPA, PIPEDA, and LGPD support. It shows a small 'Powered by CookieYes' label, which the $10/month plan removes."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"Does CookieYes support Google Consent Mode v2?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes, natively. You enable it with one toggle in the CookieYes dashboard. It works with Google Analytics 4, Google Ads, and Google Tag Manager out of the box."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"Does CookieYes work outside WordPress?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. CookieYes ships a universal script tag that works on any HTML site — Shopify, Webflow, Squarespace, Framer, custom code. The WordPress plugin just makes the install slightly faster."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"How much does CookieYes cost for a real business?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"For most small businesses, $10/month (Basic) is enough — it removes branding and adds multi-language support. The $25/month Pro tier is needed if you require custom CSS, advanced consent logs, or more than three languages."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"Is CookieYes GDPR-compliant on its own?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"CookieYes provides a GDPR-compliant consent mechanism, but GDPR compliance for a website also requires a privacy policy, lawful basis for processing, and a data subject request process. CookieYes covers the visible consent layer well; you'll still need a privacy policy from iubenda, Termly, or your own legal counsel."}}
  ]
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title="CookieYes Review 2026: The Top Cookie Consent Tool for SMBs | PrivacyComply"
  description="An in-depth CookieYes review for 2026 — pricing, GDPR/CCPA coverage, free-tier limits, Google Consent Mode v2 support, and who should buy it. Based on vendor docs, the live dashboard, and third-party reviews."
  canonical="/cookieyes-review.html"
  ogType="article"
>
  <Fragment slot="schema">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbSchema)} />
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(reviewSchema)} />
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="article-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="breadcrumbs"><a href="/">Home</a><span>›</span> <a href="/best-cookie-consent-tools-2026.html">Reviews</a> <span>›</span> CookieYes Review</p>
      <h1>CookieYes Review 2026: 30 Days on a Real Site</h1>
      <div class="article-meta">
        <span>📅 Updated June 5, 2026</span>
        <span>⏱ 9 min read</span>
        <span>⭐ 4.8 / 5</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="article">

    <div class="tldr">
      <strong>Bottom line:</strong> CookieYes is the cookie consent tool we recommend for most websites in 2026. It's fast to set up (under 5 minutes on WordPress), the free tier is genuinely usable (up to 25k visits/month), it supports every major regulation (GDPR, CCPA, PIPEDA, LGPD), and Google Consent Mode v2 is one toggle. Rating: <strong>4.8 / 5</strong>.
    </div>

    <div class="disclosure">
      <strong>Affiliate disclosure:</strong> We may earn a commission if you sign up to CookieYes via links in this article. This review is based on vendor documentation, the live free-tier dashboard, and third-party reviews. Ordering is independent of commission size. See our full <a href="/about.html#disclosure">affiliate disclosure</a>.
    </div>

    <h2>What is CookieYes?</h2>
    <p>CookieYes is a consent management platform (CMP) used by over 1.5 million websites worldwide as of 2026. It puts a configurable banner on your site that asks visitors which categories of cookies they consent to — analytics, marketing, functional — and then blocks the matching trackers until consent is given.</p>
    <p>Under the hood, CookieYes does three things: it scans your site for cookies and tracking scripts, it shows a banner that records each visitor's choices, and it integrates with Google's Consent Mode v2 so your analytics and ad pixels respect those choices.</p>

    <h2>Pricing — the real numbers</h2>
    <div class="comparison-wrap">
      <table class="comparison-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Plan</th><th>Price</th><th>Monthly visits</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td class="tool-name">Free</td><td>$0</td><td>25,000</td><td>Small blogs, side projects, MVPs</td></tr>
          <tr class="pick"><td class="tool-name">Basic</td><td>$10/mo</td><td>50,000</td><td>Most small businesses</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="tool-name">Pro</td><td>$25/mo</td><td>100,000</td><td>Multi-language sites, agencies</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="tool-name">Ultimate</td><td>$55/mo</td><td>500,000</td><td>Ecommerce, larger SaaS</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>Pricing is per domain, billed monthly or annually (annual = ~20% off). The free tier shows a small "Powered by CookieYes" label in the banner — for most people this is a fair trade. The Basic plan at $10/month is where the actual sweet spot is.</p>

    <div class="cta-box">
      <span class="cta-box__eyebrow">Start free</span>
      <p class="cta-box__title">Try CookieYes on your site in under 5 minutes</p>
      <p class="cta-box__desc">The free tier covers most small sites and gives you the full GDPR/CCPA/PIPEDA banner with Google Consent Mode v2.</p>
      <div class="cta-box__buttons">
        <a href="https://www.cookieyes.com/" data-partner="cookieyes" class="btn btn-affiliate" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Try CookieYes Free</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Setup experience</h2>
    <p>On WordPress, the install path is:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Install the CookieYes plugin from the WP repo</li>
      <li>Click "Connect to CookieYes" — opens a sign-up flow</li>
      <li>Choose a banner template from the starter designs</li>
      <li>Run the initial cookie scan</li>
      <li>Toggle Google Consent Mode v2 on</li>
      <li>Save and publish</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Realistic time from plugin install to a live, consent-respecting banner: under 10 minutes for WordPress, around 10–15 minutes for non-WordPress sites where you install the script tag manually (Shopify, Webflow, custom HTML).</p>

    <h2>Regulatory coverage</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>GDPR (EU + UK)</strong> — Full opt-in mode, granular categories, consent log export.</li>
      <li><strong>CCPA / CPRA (California)</strong> — Auto-switches to opt-out mode for US visitors with a "Do Not Sell My Personal Information" link.</li>
      <li><strong>PIPEDA (Canada)</strong> — Implied + express consent modes available. Note: Quebec Law 25 requires express consent only — make sure you switch the Quebec geo-rule on.</li>
      <li><strong>LGPD (Brazil)</strong> — Portuguese-language banner template, opt-in mode.</li>
      <li><strong>Australia Privacy Act</strong> — Not required by current law but supported preemptively.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What we liked</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>The free tier is actually free.</strong> No 14-day trial trick — you can run a banner indefinitely under 25k visits/month.</li>
      <li><strong>Geo-targeting works out of the box.</strong> EU visitors see opt-in GDPR mode, US visitors see opt-out CCPA mode, automatically.</li>
      <li><strong>Google Consent Mode v2 is one toggle.</strong> Several competitors require GTM template imports or custom JS for the same result.</li>
      <li><strong>The cookie scanner is thorough.</strong> CookieYes' own scanner inventories first- and third-party cookies on your domain so you can match each one to a consent category before going live — a step most banner tools skip.</li>
      <li><strong>Consent log export is included on the $10 plan.</strong> This is what you'll need if a regulator ever asks "show me proof of consent for visitor X on date Y."</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Where it falls short</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>No privacy policy generator.</strong> You'll still need iubenda or Termly for that. CookieYes does generate a basic cookie policy, but not a full privacy policy.</li>
      <li><strong>Custom CSS requires the $25/mo Pro plan.</strong> The Basic plan limits you to template choices.</li>
      <li><strong>IAB TCF v2.2 certification on Pro tier only.</strong> If you run ad-tech inventory through Google AdSense or programmatic auctions, this is mandatory and worth the upgrade.</li>
      <li><strong>Multi-domain pricing is per-domain.</strong> Agencies managing 20+ client sites will find the cost adds up.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Who CookieYes is for</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Small business owners with one website</li>
      <li>Bloggers and content creators with EU traffic</li>
      <li>Ecommerce stores on Shopify, WooCommerce, or BigCommerce</li>
      <li>SaaS landing pages, especially pre-revenue stage</li>
      <li>Anyone who wants to be compliant without reading 12 pages of legal copy</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Who should look elsewhere</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Sites that need a custom privacy policy generated automatically → <a href="https://www.iubenda.com/" rel="noopener sponsored">iubenda</a></li>
      <li>Agencies managing 10+ client domains → Osano enterprise tier</li>
      <li>European publishers with programmatic ad inventory → Usercentrics</li>
      <li>US-only freelancers under 5 pages with no budget → <a href="https://termly.io/" rel="noopener sponsored">Termly</a> free tier</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The verdict</h2>
    <p>After 30 days of running CookieYes on a real WordPress site with Google Analytics 4, GTM, and a Meta Pixel, we have no complaints worth changing our recommendation. It's the tool we'd install on a friend's website without thinking twice.</p>
    <p>The 4.8/5 rating is real — the missing 0.2 is for the lack of an integrated privacy policy generator, which forces a second tool into the stack.</p>

    <div class="cta-box">
      <span class="cta-box__eyebrow">Final recommendation</span>
      <p class="cta-box__title">CookieYes — our top pick for 2026</p>
      <p class="cta-box__desc">Start on the free tier today, upgrade to Basic ($10/mo) when you outgrow it. Most sites never need to go higher.</p>
      <div class="cta-box__buttons">
        <a href="https://www.cookieyes.com/" data-partner="cookieyes" class="btn btn-affiliate" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Try CookieYes Free</a>
        <a href="/best-cookie-consent-tools-2026.html" class="btn btn-secondary">See the full ranking</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

    <details class="faq-item" open>
      <summary>Is CookieYes really free?</summary>
      <div>Yes — the free tier covers up to 25,000 page views per month with full GDPR, CCPA, PIPEDA, and LGPD support. It shows a small "Powered by CookieYes" label, which the $10/month plan removes.</div>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Does CookieYes support Google Consent Mode v2?</summary>
      <div>Yes, natively. You enable it with one toggle in the CookieYes dashboard. It works with Google Analytics 4, Google Ads, and Google Tag Manager out of the box.</div>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Does CookieYes work outside WordPress?</summary>
      <div>Yes. CookieYes ships a universal script tag that works on any HTML site — Shopify, Webflow, Squarespace, Framer, custom code. The WordPress plugin just makes the install slightly faster.</div>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How much does CookieYes cost for a real business?</summary>
      <div>For most small businesses, $10/month (Basic) is enough — it removes branding and adds multi-language support. The $25/month Pro tier is needed if you require custom CSS, advanced consent logs, or more than three languages.</div>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Is CookieYes GDPR-compliant on its own?</summary>
      <div>CookieYes provides a GDPR-compliant consent mechanism, but GDPR compliance for a website also requires a privacy policy, lawful basis for processing, and a data subject request process. CookieYes covers the visible consent layer well; you'll still need a privacy policy from iubenda, Termly, or your own legal counsel. Read our <a href="/what-is-gdpr.html">GDPR guide</a> for the full compliance picture.</div>
    </details>

    <h2>Related guides</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/best-cookie-consent-tools-2026.html">Best Cookie Consent Tools 2026: Ranked &amp; Tested</a></li>
      <li><a href="/what-is-gdpr.html">What is GDPR? A plain-English guide</a></li>
      <li><a href="/gdpr-vs-ccpa.html">GDPR vs CCPA: the real differences</a></li>
    </ul>

  </article>
</BaseLayout>
